  "text": "# Kubernetes Scheduler Plugin Framework Architecture Analysis\n\n## Overview\n\nThe Kubernetes scheduler plugin framework is implemented in the `kubernetes/kubernetes` repository with key components organized in the `pkg/scheduler/` directory. The framework uses an extensible plugin architecture that allows developers to customize scheduling behavior at multiple extension points during the pod scheduling cycle.\n\n## Framework Interface Definitions\n\nThe primary interface definitions are located in **`pkg/scheduler/framework/interface.go`**, which defines:\n\n### Core Plugin Interface\n- **`Plugin`** (line 443): The parent interface that all plugins must implement, requiring only a `Name()` method.\n\n### Extension Point Plugins\n\nThe framework defines distinct plugin types for different scheduling phases:\n\n1. **Pre-Enqueue Phase**: \n   - `PreEnqueuePlugin` (line 452): Called before pods are added to the active queue, used for lightweight filtering.\n\n2. **Queue Management**:\n   - `QueueSortPlugin` (line 464): Sorts pods in the scheduling queue (only one allowed per scheduler).\n\n3. **Pre-Filter Phase**:\n   - `PreFilterPlugin` (line 512): Called at the beginning of the scheduling cycle to compute state for filtering.\n\n4. **Filter Phase**:\n   - `FilterPlugin` (line 540): Filters out nodes that cannot run a pod (replaces old \"predicate\" concept).\n\n5. **Post-Filter Phase**:\n   - `PostFilterPlugin` (line 561): Called after filtering fails, typically implements preemption logic.\n\n6. **Pre-Score Phase**:\n   - `PreScorePlugin` (line 587): Informational plugin called after filtering, before scoring.\n\n7. **Score Phase**:\n   - `ScorePlugin` (line 607): Ranks nodes for pod placement by assigning scores.\n\n8. **Reserve Phase**:\n   - `ReservePlugin` (line 624): Updates scheduler cache state when a pod is scheduled (includes Unreserve for rollback).\n\n9. **Pre-Bind Phase**:\n   - `PreBindPlugin` (line 640): Called before binding, can perform final validation or preparation.\n\n10. **Bind Phase**:\n    - `BindPlugin` (line 673): Handles actual pod-to-node binding (default binds to Kubernetes API).\n\n11. **Permit Phase**:\n    - `PermitPlugin` (line 660): Called before binding, can approve, deny, or wait for pod scheduling.\n\n12. **Post-Bind Phase**:\n    - `PostBindPlugin` (line 649): Informational plugin called after successful binding for cleanup.\n\n### Framework Interface\n- **`Framework`** (line 686): The main interface managing all plugins and orchestrating the scheduling cycle, implementing the `Handle` interface for plugin access to framework utilities.\n\n## Framework Runtime Implementation\n\nThe framework runtime is implemented in **`pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/framework.go`**:\n\n### Core Structure\n- **`frameworkImpl`** (line 52): The concrete implementation of the Framework interface that manages plugin instances and orchestrates plugin execution.\n\n### Framework Initialization\n- **`NewFramework`** (line 267): Factory function that creates a new framework instance, initializes plugins from the registry, and sets up plugin extension points.\n\n### Plugin Execution Methods\n\nThe `frameworkImpl` implements methods to run plugins at each extension point:\n\n- **`RunPreFilterPlugins`** (line 709): Executes pre-filter plugins to compute state and optionally filter nodes.\n- **`RunFilterPlugins`** (line 872): Executes filter plugins to test node feasibility.\n- **`RunPostFilterPlugins`** (line 919): Executes post-filter plugins (typically preemption) when filtering fails.\n- **`RunPreScorePlugins`** (line 1063): Executes pre-score plugins for informational purposes.\n- **`RunScorePlugins`** (line 1112): Executes score plugins in parallel to rank nodes and applies scoring weights.\n- **`RunPermitPlugins`** (line 1454): Executes permit plugins with timeout support for approval/denial.\n- **`RunPreBindPlugins`** (line 1243): Executes pre-bind plugins before pod binding.\n- **`RunBindPlugins`** (line 1286): Executes bind plugins to bind pod to node.\n- **`RunPostBindPlugins`** (line 1335): Executes post-bind plugins after successful binding.\n- **`RunReservePluginsReserve`** (line 1370): Executes reserve phase plugins to update cache state.\n- **`RunReservePluginsUnreserve`** (line 1414): Executes unreserve callbacks when scheduling fails.\n\n## Plugin Registry\n\nThe plugin registry is defined in **`pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/registry.go`**:\n\n### Registry Types\n- **`Registry`** (line 71): A map type `map[string]PluginFactory` that manages all available plugins by name. Provides `Register()`, `Unregister()`, and `Merge()` methods for plugin management.\n- **`PluginFactory`** (line 31): A function type that creates plugin instances given a context, configuration, and framework handle.\n\n### Built-in Plugins\n\nAll built-in plugins are registered in **`pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/registry.go`**:\n\n- **`NewInTreeRegistry`** (line 47): Factory function that creates a registry with all built-in Kubernetes plugins, including:\n  - **Filter Plugins**: NodeName, NodeUnschedulable, TaintToleration, NodeAffinity, NodePorts, NodeResources, VolumeRestrictions, VolumeZone, VolumeBinding, ImageLocality, InterPodAffinity, PodTopologySpread, DynamicResources, SchedulingGates\n  - **Score Plugins**: NodeResourcesFit, NodeResourcesBalancedAllocation, ImageLocality, InterPodAffinity, PodTopologySpread\n  - **Bind Plugins**: DefaultBinder\n  - **Pre/Post Plugins**: DefaultPreemption\n  - **Queue Plugins**: PrioritySort\n\nOutside plugins can be registered via `WithFrameworkOutOfTreeRegistry` option to extend the in-tree registry.\n\n## Scheduler Orchestration\n\nThe top-level scheduler orchestration is in **`pkg/scheduler/scheduler.go`**:\n\n### Scheduler Structure\n- **`Scheduler`** (line 66): Main scheduler struct that manages the scheduling cycle, maintains the pod scheduling queue, stores scheduling profiles (frameworks), and coordinates the overall scheduling workflow.\n\n### Scheduler Execution\n- **`Run`** (line 464): Entry point that starts the scheduler by running the scheduling queue and launching a goroutine to continuously call `ScheduleOne()` for each pod until context is done.\n\n## Scheduling Cycle\n\nThe single-pod scheduling cycle is implemented in **`pkg/scheduler/schedule_one.go`**:\n\n- **`ScheduleOne`** (line 65): Method that drives the complete scheduling workflow for a single pod:\n  1. Dequeues the next pod from the scheduling queue\n  2. Creates a `CycleState` for this scheduling attempt\n  3. Calls the **scheduling cycle** (via `schedulingCycle()`) which:\n     - Runs PreFilter plugins\n     - Evaluates node feasibility via Filter plugins\n     - Runs PostFilter plugins if filtering fails (preemption)\n     - Runs PreScore and Score plugins to rank remaining nodes\n     - Selects the best node\n     - Runs Permit plugins\n     - Runs Reserve plugins to update cache state\n  4. If successful, launches a separate **binding cycle** (via `bindingCycle()`) that:\n     - Runs PreBind plugins\n     - Runs Bind plugins to bind pod to node\n     - Runs PostBind plugins\n     - Marks pod as scheduled\n  5. Handles failures appropriately with preemption or requeuing\n\n## Extension Point Sequence\n\nThe complete plugin execution sequence during the scheduling cycle:\n\n1. **PreEnqueue** → Pod enqueue decision\n2. **QueueSort** → Pod priority in queue\n3. **PreFilter** → Pre-calculate filtering state\n4. **Filter** → Node feasibility testing\n5. **PostFilter** → Preemption when no nodes pass\n6. **PreScore** → Informational before scoring\n7. **Score** → Node ranking (parallel)\n8. **Permit** → Final approval before binding\n9. **Reserve** → Cache state update\n10. **PreBind** → Pre-binding preparation\n11. **Bind** → Pod-to-node binding\n12. **PostBind** → Post-binding cleanup\n\n## Key Architectural Patterns\n\n1. **Plugin Composition**: All plugins implement the lightweight `Plugin` interface and optionally extend it with specific extension point interfaces.\n2. **Registry Pattern**: Plugins are discovered and instantiated via the `Registry` map, allowing for easy extension.\n3. **Cycle State**: Each scheduling attempt gets its own `CycleState` to maintain isolated state across plugins.\n4. **Parallelization**: Score plugins and other expensive operations are parallelized using the framework's `Parallelizer` utility.\n5. **Metrics Recording**: Plugin execution is instrumented with duration and status metrics for observability.\n6. **Preemption Support**: PostFilter plugins enable sophisticated preemption logic to make unschedulable pods schedulable.\n7. **Out-of-Tree Support**: The architecture supports external plugins through the registry merge mechanism.\n\n## Repository References\n\nAll components are located in the `kubernetes/kubernetes` repository version v1.32.0, in the scheduler package under `pkg/scheduler/`."
}

